# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: non-proteinogenic-amino-acids
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] 2-Aminoisobutyric acid can be prepared from acetone cyanohydrin, by reaction with ammonia followed by hydrolysis.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The compound is not chiral, unlike most amino acids.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] It is a strong helix inducer in peptides due to Thorpe–Ingold effect of its gem-dimethyl group.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] 2-Aminoisobutyric acid is not one of the proteinogenic amino acids and is rather rare in nature (*cf.* non-proteinogenic amino acids).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] In the context of cell-free protein synthesis 2-aminoisobutyric acid is compatible with ribosomal elongation of peptide synthesis.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Flexizymes and an engineered tRNA body enhance the affinity of aminoacylated Aib-tRNA species to elongation factor P.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The result was an increased incorporation of Aib into peptides in a cell free translation system.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Iqbal *et al.*. used an alternative approach of creating an editing deficient valine—tRNA ligase to synthesize aminoacylated Aib-tRNAVal.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] The aminoacylated tRNA was subsequently used in a cell-free translation system to yield Aib-containing peptides.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/2-aminoisobutyric-acid] Aib has been found in meteorites and some antibiotics of fungal origin, such as alamethicin and some lantibiotics.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Food sources of PABA include liver, brewer's yeast (and unfiltered beer), kidney, molasses, mushrooms, and whole grains.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other food sources of PABA include spinach and oat seeds.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is an intermediate in the synthesis of folate by bacteria, plants, and fungi.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Many bacteria, including those found in the human intestinal tract such as *E. coli*, generate PABA from chorismate by the combined action of the enzymes 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate synthase and 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate lyase.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Plants produce PABA in their chloroplasts, and store it as a glucose ester (*p*ABA-Glc) in their tissues.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The malarial protozoan *Plasmodium* only make PABA when necessary, preferring to get it from the surroundings if able to.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Some bacteria, including a few found in the human microbiome, are unable to make PABA for themselves but can use PABA to make folate.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] A few are very efficient at the PABA-to-folate conversion despite not making their own PABA.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Sulfonamide drugs are structurally similar to PABA, and their antibacterial activity is due to their ability to interfere with the conversion of PABA to folate by the enzyme dihydropteroate synthetase.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Thus, bacterial growth is limited through folate deficiency.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA has been referred to historically as "vitamin Bx", but plays no direct role in animal cells and is hence no longer recognized as a vitamin.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Animals (including humans) are unable to use PABA in any way and so require folate from dietary sources such as green leafy vegetables.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA can play a role in the supply of folate to an animal via its microbiome; this is best demonstrated in the worm *C. elegans*, in which addition of PABA could increase folate production by resident *E. coli* and correct for deficiencies.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The *C. elegans* folate transporter only works with the reduced form (tetrahydrofolate, THF and derivatives such as folinic acid), not regular folic acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Any folic acid from the environment is only usable following spontaneous breakdown to PABA-glu, which *E. coli* uses to make THF.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In contrast, humans can directly use oxidized folates thanks to the proton-coupled folate transporter and have no need for this detour; this "recycling" of PABA-glu would, at best, compensate for folate degredation.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The above do not seem to apply in normal mammals, however.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite detection of gut-produced folate being incorporated into mammals, *ex vivo* folate synthesis capacity of fecal bacteria have no correlation with the folate status of their donors.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Furthermore, comparison with germ-free animals show that under a chow diet, the mouse microbiome is a net consumer of folate.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The caveat is that the mouse chow is more folate-rich than typical human diets and may be encouraging a shift towards a folate-consuming microbiome.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] There are no reports of any usefulness of PABA in germ-free animals.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA and its salts are used in nutritional epidemiological studies to assess the completeness of 24-hour urine collection for the determination of urinary sodium, potassium, or nitrogen levels.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The potassium salt (potassium paraaminobenzoate, "aminobenzoate potassium") is used as a drug against fibrotic skin disorders, such as Peyronie's disease, under the brand name Potaba.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is believed to work by inhibiting fibroblast glycosaminoglycan secretion and stabilizing monoamine oxidase A activity.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also occasionally used in pill form by sufferers of irritable bowel syndrome to treat its associated gastrointestinal symptoms.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA derivatives have also been proposed to function as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors in diseases that cause deficient cholinergic systems, such as Alzheimer's Disease.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Despite the lack of any recognized syndromes of PABA deficiency in humans, except for those who lack the colonic bacteria that generate PABA, many claims of benefit are made by commercial suppliers of PABA as a nutritional supplement.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The benefit is claimed for fatigue, irritability, depression, weeping eczema (moist eczema), scleroderma (premature hardening of the skin), patchy pigment loss in the skin (vitiligo), and premature grey hair.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA finds use in the biomedical sector.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Its derivatives are found as a structural component in 1.5% of a database of 12111 commercial drugs.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Other uses include its conversion to specialty azo dyes and crosslinking agents.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is also used as a biodegradable pesticide, though its use is now limited due to evolution of new variants of bio-pesticides.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Specifically, studies have shown that PABA photodegrades through an O2-mediated pathway in which PABA is oxidized by O2 via hydrogen abstraction and decarboxylation.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In the past, PABA was widely used in sunscreens as a UV filter.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is a UVB absorber, meaning it can absorb wavelengths between 290 and 320 nm. while still allowing UVA wavelengths between 320-400 nm to pass through, producing a tan.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The chemical structure of PABA, with the amino and carboxyl groups being *para* to each other, allows for easy electron delocalization, which reduces the gap between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] This makes it easier for the electrons in PABA to transition to a higher energy state upon absorbing light.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Patented in 1943, PABA was one of the first active ingredients to be used in sunscreen.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] The first *in vivo* studies on mice showed that PABA reduced UV damage.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In addition, it was shown to protect against skin tumors in rodents, as shown by a 1975 study ran by Dr.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, animal and *in vitro* studies in the early 1980s suggested PABA might increase the risk of cellular UV damage.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] On the basis of these studies, as well as problems with allergies and clothing discoloration, PABA fell out of favor as a sunscreen.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] In 2008 it was banned as a sunscreen ingredient in the European Union and in 2019 the FDA proposed its limited use.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] However, water-insoluble PABA derivatives such as padimate O are currently used in some cosmetic products including mascara, concealer, and matte lipsticks.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] As of 2008, the advancement of new sunscreen is focused on developing a broad spectrum of active ingredients that provide consistent protection across all wavelengths, including UVA.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Researchers are considering the PABA–TiO2 Hybrid Nanostructures that result from the method of aqueous in situ synthesis with PABA and TiO2.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] PABA is largely nontoxic; the median lethal dose of PABA in dogs (oral) is 2 g/kg.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] Allergic reactions, specifically allergic contact dermatitis and photocontact dermatitis, to PABA can occur.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/4-aminobenzoic-acid] It is formed in the metabolism of certain ester-type local anesthetics, and many allergic reactions to local anesthetics are the result of reactions to PABA.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A chiral object and its reflection are called *enantiomorphs* (from Greek for 'opposite forms') or, when referring to molecules, *enantiomers*.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Chirality is a property of asymmetry important in several branches of science.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Human hands are perhaps the most recognized example of chirality.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The left hand is a non-superposable mirror image of the right hand; no matter how the two hands are oriented, it is impossible for all the major features of both hands to coincide across all axes.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This difference in symmetry becomes obvious if someone attempts to shake the right hand of a person using their left hand, or if a left-handed glove is placed on a right hand.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The word *chirality* is derived from the Ancient Greek χείρ (*kheír*), meaning 'hand', a familiar chiral object.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In mathematics, a figure is chiral (and said to have chirality) if it cannot be mapped to its mirror image by rotations and translations alone.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For example, a right shoe is different from a left shoe, and S-twist yarn is different from Z-twist.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A chiral object and its mirror image are said to be enantiomorphs.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The word *enantiomorph* stems from the Greek ἐναντίος (*enantios*) 'opposite' + μορφή (*morphe*) 'form'.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A non-chiral figure is called achiral or amphichiral.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The helix (and by extension a spun string, a screw, a propeller, etc.) and Möbius strip are chiral two-dimensional objects in three-dimensional ambient space.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The J, L, S and Z-shaped *tetrominoes* of the popular video game Tetris also exhibit chirality, but only in a two-dimensional space.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Many other familiar objects exhibit the same chiral symmetry of the human body, such as gloves, glasses (sometimes), and shoes.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A similar notion of chirality is considered in knot theory, as explained below.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Some chiral three-dimensional objects, such as the helix, can be assigned a right or left handedness, according to the right-hand rule.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In geometry, a figure is achiral if and only if its symmetry group contains at least one *orientation-reversing* isometry.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In two dimensions, every figure that possesses an axis of symmetry is achiral, and it can be shown that every *bounded* achiral figure must have an axis of symmetry.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In three dimensions, every figure that possesses a plane of symmetry or a center of symmetry is achiral.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] There are, however, achiral figures lacking both plane and center of symmetry.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In terms of point groups, all chiral figures lack an improper axis of rotation (Sn).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This means that they cannot contain a center of inversion (i) or a mirror plane (σ).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Only figures with a point group designation of C1, Cn, Dn, T, O, or I can be chiral.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A knot is called achiral if it can be continuously deformed into its mirror image, otherwise it is called chiral.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For example, the unknot and the figure-eight knot are achiral, whereas the trefoil knot is chiral.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In physics, chirality may be found in the spin of a particle, where the handedness of the object is determined by the direction in which the particle spins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Not to be confused with helicity, which is the projection of the spin along the linear momentum of a subatomic particle, chirality is an intrinsic quantum mechanical property, like spin.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Although both chirality and helicity can have left-handed or right-handed properties, only in the massless case are they identical.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In particular for a massless particle the helicity is the same as the chirality while for an antiparticle they have opposite sign.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The *handedness* in both chirality and helicity relate to the rotation of a particle while it proceeds in linear motion with reference to the human hands.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The thumb of the hand points towards the direction of linear motion whilst the fingers curl into the palm, representing the direction of rotation of the particle (i.e. clockwise and counterclockwise).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Depending on the linear and rotational motion, the particle can either be defined by left-handedness or right-handedness.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A symmetry transformation between the two is called parity.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Invariance under parity by a Dirac fermion is called *chiral symmetry*.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Electromagnetic waves can have handedness associated with their polarization.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Polarization of an electromagnetic wave is the property that describes the orientation, i.e., the time-varying direction and amplitude, of the electric field vector.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For example, the electric field vectors of left-handed or right-handed circularly polarized waves form helices of opposite handedness in space.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Circularly polarized waves of opposite handedness propagate through chiral media at different speeds (circular birefringence) and with different losses (circular dichroism).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Both phenomena are jointly known as optical activity.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Circular birefringence causes rotation of the polarization state of electromagnetic waves in chiral media and can cause a negative index of refraction for waves of one handedness when the effect is sufficiently large.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] While optical activity occurs in structures that are chiral in three dimensions (such as helices), the concept of chirality can also be applied in two dimensions.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] 2D-chiral patterns, such as flat spirals, cannot be superposed with their mirror image by translation or rotation in two-dimensional space (a plane).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] 2D chirality is associated with directionally asymmetric transmission (reflection and absorption) of circularly polarized waves.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] 2D-chiral materials, which are also anisotropic and lossy exhibit different total transmission (reflection and absorption) levels for the same circularly polarized wave incident on their front and back.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The asymmetric transmission phenomenon arises from different, e.g. left-to-right, circular polarization conversion efficiencies for opposite propagation directions of the incident wave and therefore the effect is referred to as circular conversion dichroism.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Like the twist of a 2d-chiral pattern appears reversed for opposite directions of observation, 2d-chiral materials have interchanged properties for left-handed and right-handed circularly polarized waves that are incident on their front and back.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In particular left-handed and right-handed circularly polarized waves experience opposite directional transmission (reflection and absorption) asymmetries.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] While optical activity is associated with 3d chirality and circular conversion is associated with 2d chirality, both effects have also been observed in structures that are not chiral by themselves.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For the observation of these chiral electromagnetic effects, chirality does not have to be an intrinsic property of the material that interacts with the electromagnetic wave.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Instead, both effects can also occur when the propagation direction of the electromagnetic wave together with the structure of an (achiral) material form a chiral experimental arrangement.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This case, where the mutual arrangement of achiral components forms a chiral (experimental) arrangement, is known as extrinsic chirality.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Chiral mirrors are a class of metamaterials that reflect circularly polarized light of a certain helicity in a handedness-preserving manner, while absorbing circular polarization of the opposite handedness.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] However, most absorbing chiral mirrors operate only in a narrow frequency band, as limited by the causality principle.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Employing a different design methodology that allows undesired waves to pass through instead of absorbing the undesired waveform, chiral mirrors are able to show good broadband performance.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A *chiral molecule* is a type of molecule that has a non-superposable mirror image.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The feature that is most often the cause of chirality in molecules is the presence of an asymmetric carbon atom.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The term "chiral" in general is used to describe the object that is non-superposable on its mirror image.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In chemistry, chirality usually refers to molecules.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Two mirror images of a chiral molecule are called enantiomers or optical isomers.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Pairs of enantiomers are often designated as "right-", "left-handed" or, if they have no bias, "achiral".
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] As polarized light passes through a chiral molecule, the plane of polarization, when viewed along the axis toward the source, will be rotated clockwise (to the right) or anticlockwise (to the left).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A right handed rotation is dextrorotary (d); that to the left is levorotary (l).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The d- and l-isomers are the same compound but are called enantiomers.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] An equimolar mixture of the two optical isomers, which is called a racemic mixture, will produce no net rotation of polarized light as it passes through.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Left handed molecules have l- prefixed to their names; d- is prefixed to right handed molecules.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] However, this *d-* and *l-* notation of distinguishing enantiomers does not say anything about the actual spatial arrangement of the ligands/substituents around the stereogenic center, which is defined as configuration.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Another nomenclature system employed to specify configuration is Fischer convention.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This is also referred to as the D- and L-system.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Here the relative configuration is assigned with reference to D-(+)-Glyceraldehyde and L-(−)-Glyceraldehyde, being taken as standard.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Fischer convention is widely used in sugar chemistry and for α-amino acids.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Due to the drawbacks of Fischer convention, it is almost entirely replaced by Cahn-Ingold-Prelog convention, also known as the sequence rule or R and S nomenclature.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This was further extended to assign absolute configuration to *cis-trans* isomers with the E-Z notation.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Molecular chirality is of interest because of its application to stereochemistry in inorganic chemistry, organic chemistry, physical chemistry, biochemistry, and supramolecular chemistry.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] More recent developments in chiral chemistry include the development of chiral inorganic nanoparticles that may have the similar tetrahedral geometry as chiral centers associated with sp3 carbon atoms traditionally associated with chiral compounds, but at larger scale.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Helical and other symmetries of chiral nanomaterials were also obtained.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] All of the known life-forms show specific chiral properties in chemical structures as well as macroscopic anatomy, development and behavior.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In any specific organism or evolutionarily related set thereof, individual compounds, organs, or behavior are found in the same single enantiomorphic form.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Deviation (having the opposite form) could be found in a small number of chemical compounds, or certain organ or behavior but that variation strictly depends upon the genetic make up of the organism.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] From chemical level (molecular scale), biological systems show extreme stereospecificity in synthesis, uptake, sensing, metabolic processing.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A living system usually deals with two enantiomers of the same compound in drastically different ways.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In biology, homochirality is a common property of amino acids and carbohydrates.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The chiral protein-making amino acids, which are translated through the ribosome from genetic coding, occur in the L form.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] However, D-amino acids are also found in nature.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] The monosaccharides (carbohydrate-units) are commonly found in D-configuration.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] DNA double helix is chiral (as any kind of helix is chiral), and B-form of DNA shows a right-handed turn.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Sometimes, when two enantiomers of a compound are found in organisms, they significantly differ in their taste, smell and other biological actions.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For example,(+)-Carvone is responsible for the smell of caraway seed oil, whereas (–)-carvone is responsible for smell of spearmint oil.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] However, it is a commonly held misconception that (+)-limonene is found in oranges (causing its smell), and (–)-limonene is found in lemons (causing its smell).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In 2021, after rigorous experimentation, it was found that all citrus fruits contain only (+)-limonene and the odor difference is because of other contributing factors.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Also, for artificial compounds, including medicines, in case of chiral drugs, the two enantiomers sometimes show remarkable difference in effect of their biological actions.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Dextropropoxyphene (Darvon) is a painkiller, whereas its enantiomer, levopropoxyphene (Novrad) is an anti-cough agent.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In case of penicillamine, the (*S*-isomer is used in the treatment of primary chronic arthritis, whereas the (*R*)-isomer has no therapeutic effect, as well as being highly toxic.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In some cases, the less therapeutically active enantiomer can cause side effects.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] For example, (*S*-naproxen is an analgesic but the (*R*-isomer causes renal problems.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In such situations where one of the enantiomers of a racemic drug is active and the other partner has undesirable or toxic effect one may switch from racemate to a single enantiomer drug for a better therapeutic value.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Such a switching from a racemic drug to an enantiopure drug is called a chiral switch.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Macroscopic examples of chirality are found in the plant kingdom, the animal kingdom and all other groups of organisms.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A simple example is the coiling direction of any climber plant, which can grow to form either a left- or right-handed helix.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In anatomy, chirality is found in the imperfect mirror image symmetry of many kinds of animal bodies.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Organisms such as gastropods exhibit chirality in their coiled shells, resulting in an asymmetrical appearance.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Over 90% of gastropod species have *dextral* (right-handed) shells in their coiling, but a small minority of species and genera are virtually always *sinistral* (left-handed).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] A very few species (for example *Amphidromus perversus*) show an equal mixture of dextral and sinistral individuals.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In humans, chirality (also referred to as *handedness* or *laterality*) is an attribute of humans defined by their unequal distribution of fine motor skill between the left and right hands.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] An individual who is more dexterous with the right hand is called *right-handed*, and one who is more skilled with the left is said to be *left-handed*.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Chirality is also seen in the study of facial asymmetry and is known as aurofacial asymmetry.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] According to the Axial Twist theory, vertebrate animals develop into a left-handed chirality.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Due to this, the brain is turned around and the heart and bowels are turned by 90°.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In the monocot bloodroot family, the species of the genera *Wachendorfia* and *Barberetta* have only individuals that either have the style points to the right or the style pointed to the left, with both morphs appearing within the same populations.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] This is thought to increase outcrossing and so boost genetic diversity, which in turn may help to survive in a changing environment.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] Remarkably, the related genus *Dilatris* also has chirally dimorphic flowers, but here both morphs occur on the same plant.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/achiral] In flatfish, the summer flounder or fluke are left-eyed, while halibut are right-eyed.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/adda-amino-acid] Along with leucine and arginine, it is found in microcystin-LR, an extremely toxic compound produced by cyanobacteria.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/adda-amino-acid] In order to treat a water supply contaminated with microcystin-LR, chlorination can be used to oxidize the double bonds of ADDA in order to initiate the chemical breakdown of this compound.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alloisoleucine] Together with valine, leucine, and isoleucine, alloisoleucine is classified as a branched-chain amino acid (BCAA).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alloisoleucine] The L enantiomer of valine, leucine, and isoleucine are proteinogenic amino acids; alloisoleucine is non-proteinogenic.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/alloisoleucine] L-Alloisoleucine is a precursor to coronatine, a phytotoxin produced by *Pseudomonas syringae*.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/allothreonine] Threonine has R, S stereochemistry at carbons 2 and 3 for the naturally occurring stereoisomer and S, R stereochemistry for its enantiomer.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/allothreonine] Allothreonine has S, S stereochemistry at carbons 2 and 3 in the natural stereoisomer, but R, R in the very rare enantiomer.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/allothreonine] Katanosins are a group of potent antibiotics containing allothreonine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/allothreonine] Peptides containing the allothreonine residue have also been isolated from natural sources.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In biochemistry, **non-coded** or **non-proteinogenic amino acids** are distinct from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids (21 in eukaryotes), which are naturally encoded in the genome of organisms for the assembly of proteins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] However, over 140 non-proteinogenic amino acids occur naturally in proteins (but not included in the genetic code) and thousands more may occur in nature or be synthesized in the laboratory.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Chemically synthesized amino acids are often referred to as **unnatural** or **non-canonical amino acids**.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Unnatural amino acids can be synthetically prepared from their native analogs via modifications such as amine alkylation, side chain substitution, structural bond extension cyclization, and isosteric replacements within the amino acid backbone.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Technically, any organic compound with an amine (–NH2) and a carboxylic acid (–COOH) functional group is an amino acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The genetic code encodes 20 standard amino acids for incorporation into proteins during translation.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] However, there are two extra proteinogenic amino acids: selenocysteine and pyrrolysine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] These non-standard amino acids do not have a dedicated codon, but are added in place of a stop codon when a specific sequence is present, UGA codon and SECIS element for selenocysteine, UAG PYLIS downstream sequence for pyrrolysine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] All other amino acids are termed "non-proteinogenic".
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] These groups overlap, but are not identical.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] All 22 proteinogenic amino acids are biosynthesised by organisms and some, but not all, of them also are abiotic (found in prebiotic experiments and meteorites).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Some natural amino acids, such as norleucine, are misincorporated translationally into proteins due to infidelity of the protein-synthesis process.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Many amino acids, such as ornithine, are metabolic intermediates produced biosynthetically, but not incorporated translationally into proteins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Post-translational modification of amino acid residues in proteins leads to the formation of many proteinaceous, but non-proteinogenic, amino acids.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Other amino acids are solely found in abiotic mixes (e.g. α-methylnorvaline).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Over 30 unnatural amino acids have been inserted translationally into proteins in engineered systems, yet are not biosynthetic.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Most natural amino acids are α-amino acids in the L configuration, but some exceptions exist.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Some non-α-amino acids exist in organisms.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In these structures, the amine group is displaced further from the carboxylic acid end of the amino acid molecule.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Thus a β-amino acid has the amine group bonded to the second carbon away, and a γ-amino acid has it on the third.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Examples include β-alanine, GABA, and δ-aminolevulinic acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The reason why α-amino acids are used in proteins has been linked to their frequency in meteorites and prebiotic experiments.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] An initial speculation on the deleterious properties of β-amino acids in terms of secondary structure turned out to be incorrect.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Some amino acids contain the opposite absolute chirality, chemicals that are not available from normal ribosomal translation and transcription machinery.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Most bacterial cells walls are formed by peptidoglycan, a polymer composed of amino sugars crosslinked with short oligopeptides bridged between each other.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The oligopeptide is non-ribosomally synthesised and contains several peculiarities including D-amino acids, generally D-alanine and D-glutamate.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] A further peculiarity is that the former is racemised by a PLP-binding enzymes (encoded by *alr* or the homologue *dadX*), whereas the latter is racemised by a cofactor independent enzyme (*murI*).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Some variants are present, in *Thermotoga* spp.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] D-Lysine is present and in certain vancomycin-resistant bacteria D-serine is present (*vanT* gene).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] All proteinogenic amino acids have at least one hydrogen on the α-carbon.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Glycine has two hydrogens, and all others have one hydrogen and one side-chain.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Replacement of the remaining hydrogen with a larger substituent, such as a methyl group, distorts the protein backbone.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In some fungi α-aminoisobutyric acid is produced as a precursor to peptides, some of which exhibit antibiotic properties.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] This compound is similar to alanine, but possesses an additional methyl group on the α-carbon instead of a hydrogen.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Another compound similar to alanine without an α-hydrogen is dehydroalanine, which possesses a methylene sidechain.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] It is one of several naturally occurring dehydroamino acids.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] A subset of L-α-amino acids are ambiguous as to which of two ends is the α-carbon.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In proteins a cysteine residue can form a disulfide bond with another cysteine residue, thus crosslinking the protein.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Two crosslinked cysteines form a cystine molecule.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Cysteine and methionine are generally produced by direct sulfurylation, but in some species they can be produced by transsulfuration, where the activated homoserine or serine is fused to a cysteine or homocysteine forming cystathionine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] A similar compound is lanthionine, which can be seen as two alanine molecules joined via a thioether bond and is found in various organisms.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Similarly, djenkolic acid, a plant toxin from jengkol beans, is composed of two cysteines connected by a methylene group.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Diaminopimelic acid is both used as a bridge in peptidoglycan and is used a precursor to lysine (via its decarboxylation).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In meteorites and in prebiotic experiments (e.g.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Miller–Urey experiment) many more amino acids than the twenty standard amino acids are found, several of which are at higher concentrations than the standard ones.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] It has been conjectured that if amino acid based life were to arise elsewhere in the universe, no more than 75% of the amino acids would be in common.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The most notable anomaly is the lack of aminobutyric acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The genetic code has been described as a frozen accident and the reasons why there is only one standard amino acid with a straight chain, alanine, could simply be redundancy with valine, leucine and isoleucine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] However, straight chained amino acids are reported to form much more stable alpha helices.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Serine, homoserine, *O*-methylhomoserine and *O*-ethylhomoserine possess a hydroxymethyl, hydroxyethyl, *O*-methylhydroxymethyl and *O*-methylhydroxyethyl side chain; whereas cysteine, homocysteine, methionine and ethionine possess the thiol equivalents.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The selenol equivalents are selenocysteine, selenohomocysteine, selenomethionine and selenoethionine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Amino acids with the next chalcogen down are also found in nature: several species such as *Aspergillus fumigatus*, *Aspergillus terreus*, and *Penicillium chrysogenum* in the absence of sulfur are able to produce and incorporate into protein tellurocysteine and telluromethionine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In cells, especially autotrophs, several non-proteinogenic amino acids are found as metabolic intermediates.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] However, despite the catalytic flexibility of PLP-binding enzymes, many amino acids are synthesised as keto acids (such as 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoate to leucine) and aminated in the last step, thus keeping the number of non-proteinogenic amino acid intermediates fairly low.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] In addition to primary metabolism, several non-proteinogenic amino acids are precursors or the final production in secondary metabolism to make small compounds or non-ribosomal peptides (such as some toxins).
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Despite not being encoded by the genetic code as proteinogenic amino acids, some non-standard amino acids are nevertheless found in proteins.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] These are formed by post-translational modification of the side chains of standard amino acids present in the target protein.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] These modifications are often essential for the function or regulation of a protein; for example, in γ-carboxyglutamate the carboxylation of glutamate allows for better binding of calcium cations, and in hydroxyproline the hydroxylation of proline is critical for maintaining connective tissues.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Another example is the formation of hypusine in the translation initiation factor EIF5A, through modification of a lysine residue.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, for example, the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] There is some preliminary evidence that aminomalonic acid may be present, possibly by misincorporation, in protein.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Several non-proteinogenic amino acids are toxic due to their ability to mimic certain properties of proteinogenic amino acids, such as thialysine.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are neurotoxic by mimicking amino acids used as neurotransmitters (that is, not for protein biosynthesis), including quisqualic acid, canavanine, caramboxin and azetidine-2-carboxylic acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Cephalosporin C has an α-aminoadipic acid (homoglutamate) backbone that is amidated with a cephalosporin moiety.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Penicillamine is a therapeutic amino acid, whose mode of action is unknown.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Naturally occurring cyanotoxins can also include non-proteinogenic amino acids.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] Microcystin and nodularin, for example, are both derived from ADDA, a β-amino acid.
[src:non-proteinogenic-amino-acids/non-proteinogenic-amino-acids] The osmolytes, sarcosine and glycine betaine are derived from amino acids, but have a secondary and quaternary amine respectively.
